CVE-2026-54273: Bound pipelined request queue per connection

Bespoke backport of upstream PR #12830 (commit 93a2b1c) and 3.14 backport
PR #12854 (commit dfdfa9d) for aiohttp 3.13.3.

aiohttp <= 3.14.0 did not impose a limit on the number of HTTP/1 pipelined
requests buffered per server connection. A remote attacker could pipeline
many requests against a connection where the handler was slow to consume
them, growing the in-memory request queue unboundedly and exhausting
server memory (CWE-770). Fixed upstream in 3.14.1 by introducing
MAX_MSG_QUEUE_SIZE=32 and pausing the transport when the per-connection
queue is full, resuming below a low-water mark.

This 3.13.3 backport diverges from the upstream patch because the
prerequisite parser-aware BaseProtocol refactor and HeadersParser/HttpParser
API changes did not land in 3.13.x. Per the research recommendation, the
port:

  * adds the bound-queue logic (max_msg_queue_size kwarg, _msg_in_flight,
    message_consumed(), and the queue-full early-return in feed_data) to
    the pure-Python HttpParser/HttpRequestParser AND the Cython
    HttpParser/HttpRequestParser (rebuild required for the C extension);
  * pauses/resumes the transport directly from RequestHandler with a
    local _msg_queue_paused flag, instead of routing through the
    BaseProtocol _reading_paused_for_msg_queue() hook (which does not
    exist in 3.13.3);
  * carries the upstream tests that exercise the public surface
    (max_msg_queue_size kwarg, message_consumed, MAX_MSG_QUEUE_SIZE,
    end-to-end pipelined-queue cap and resume); the new
    tests/test_web_protocol.py file is intentionally not included as it
    targets the missing parser-aware refactor.

